{"cursor":"27079","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox monarch |image =Hutchinsonsstory00londuoft 0169.jpg |caption\n=Ajatashatru of Magadha makes a midnight call |birth_name = |birth_date =\n|birth_place = |death_date =461 BCE |death_place = |royal house =Haryanka\ndynasty |other_names = |known for = |title = Emperor of the Magadha Empire\n|reign = 492 BC â c. 460 BCE |predecessor =Bimbisara |successor\n=Udayabhadra |father =Bimbisara |spouse =Princess Vajira |children\n=Udayabhadra |religion =Jain }}\n\n\n in Rajgir, where his ashes were interred]]\n\n'Ajatasatru' (Sanskrit à¤à¤à¤¾à¤¤à¤¶à¤¤à¥à¤°à¥, AjataÅatru, Tibetan à½à¼à½¦à¾à¾±à½ºà½¦à¼à½à½à¾²à¼; ruled c. 492\nBC â c. 460 BC) was a king of the Magadha empire in north India. He was the son\nof King Bimbisara, the great monarch of Magadha. He was contemporary to Mahavira\nand Buddha. He took over the kingdom of Magadha from his father forcefully by\nimprisoning him. He fought a terrible war against the Vajjis/Lichhvis and\nconquered the once considered invincible democratic Vaishali Republic. He\nfollowed the policy of conquest and expansion. He defeated his neighbours\nincluding the king of Kosala; his brother occupied Kashi which was given to\nBimbisara as dowry. This led to a war between Magadha and Kosala. Ajatshatru\noccupied Kashi and captured the smaller kingdoms. Ajatshatru's Magadha became\nthe most powerful kingdom in Northern India and its power was felt far and wide.\n","linknr":266,"url":"Ajatashatru","recorded":1375072997,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ajatasatru&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ajatasatru&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Ajatasatru","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Cch